# Turmeric Drum Alloy Optimization

## Project Overview

This project focuses on the computational design and optimization of a wear-resistant, food-compatible alloy for a turmeric separator drum used in industrial turmeric processing.

The work combines:

* Materials engineering
* Computational alloy design
* CALPHAD methodology
* Python-based virtual alloy generation

The goal is to identify an alloy suitable for:

* corrosion resistance
* abrasive wear resistance
* food-processing compatibility
* manufacturability

for a rotary turmeric separator drum.

---

## Alloy System

The candidate alloy family explored:

**Fe–Cr–Ni–Mo–Mn**

based on a modified stainless-steel concept.

Target composition window:

| Element | Range         |
| ------- | ------------- |
| Cr      | 16–19 wt%     |
| Ni      | 6–9 wt%       |
| Mo      | 1–3 wt%       |
| Mn      | 1–4 wt%       |
| C       | 0.01–0.05 wt% |
| Si      | 0.2–0.8 wt%   |
| Fe      | Balance       |

---

## Candidate C Baseline

Target alloy:

Fe(balance)-Cr18-Ni8-Mo2.5-Mn2

Designed to achieve:

* High FCC stability
* Low sigma phase formation
* Good corrosion resistance
* Improved wear resistance

